.TH OWM 1 owm\-VERSION
.SH NAME
owm \- oarix's dynamic window manager
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B owm
.RB [ \-v ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
owm is a window manager for X11 based on DWM. It manages windows in tiled, monocle
and floating layouts. Either layout can be applied dynamically, optimising the
environment for the application in use and the task performed.
.P
In tiled layouts windows are managed in a master and stacking area. The master
area on the left contains one window by default, and the stacking area on the
right contains all other windows. The number of master area windows can be
adjusted from zero to an arbitrary number. In monocle layout all windows are
maximised to the screen size. In floating layout windows can be resized and
moved freely. Dialog windows are always managed floating, regardless of the
layout applied.
.P
Windows are grouped by tags. Each window can be tagged with one or multiple
tags. Selecting certain tags displays all windows with these tags. Five tags
are available by default (1 through 5). Certain applications have predefined 
rules; for instance, Firefox automatically opens on tag 1.
.P
Each screen contains a small status bar which displays all available tags, the
layout, and the title of the focused window. A floating window is indicated with an
empty square and a maximised floating window is indicated with a filled square
before the windows title. The selected tags are indicated with a different
color (blue background). The tags of the focused window are indicated with a filled square in the
top left corner. The tags which are applied to one or more windows are
indicated with an empty square in the top left corner.
.P
owm draws a 2-pixel border around windows to indicate the focus state, and 
maintains a 15-pixel gap between all tiled windows.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-v
prints version information to stderr, then exits.
.SH USAGE
.SS Status bar
.TP
.B Status Text Area
The status text area displays dynamic system information (Memory, Battery, and Time) via 
an internal block update mechanism, refreshing every 30 seconds.
.TP
.B Button1
click on a tag label to display all windows with that tag, click on the layout
label toggles between tiled and floating layout.
.TP
.B Button3
click on a tag label adds/removes all windows with that tag to/from the view.
.TP
.B Mod\-Button1
click on a tag label applies that tag to the focused window.
.TP
.B Mod\-Button3
click on a tag label adds/removes that tag to/from the focused window.
.SS Keyboard commands
The modifier key \fBMod\fR is defined as the Super/Windows key (Mod4Mask) by default, 
or the Alt key (Mod1Mask) in debug builds.
.TP
.B Mod\-space
Spawn
.BR dmenu(1)
for launching other programs.
.TP
.B Mod\-Return
Start
.BR st(1).
.TP
.B Mod\-b
Start firefox.
.TP
.B Mod\-e
Start nautilus.
.TP
.B Mod\-w
Start dmenu_wallpaper.
.TP
.B Mod\-Shift\-b
Toggles bar on and off.
.TP
.B Mod\-j
Focus next window.
.TP
.B Mod\-k
Focus previous window.
.TP
.B Mod\-i
Increase number of windows in master area.
.TP
.B Mod\-d
Decrease number of windows in master area.
.TP
.B Mod\-h
Decrease master area size.
.TP
.B Mod\-l
Increase master area size.
.TP
.B Mod\-s
Zooms/cycles focused window to/from master area (tiled layouts only).
.TP
.B Mod\-Tab
Toggles to the previously selected tags.
.TP
.B Mod\-q
Close focused window.
.TP
.B Mod\-t
Sets tiled layout.
.TP
.B Mod\-f
Sets floating layout.
.TP
.B Mod\-m
Sets monocle layout.
.TP
.B Mod\-[1..5]
View all windows with nth tag.
.TP
.B Mod\-Shift\-[1..5]
Apply nth tag to focused window.
.TP
.B Mod\-Control\-[1..5]
Add/remove all windows with nth tag to/from the view.
.TP
.B Mod\-Control\-Shift\-[1..5]
Add/remove nth tag to/from focused window.
.TP
.B Mod\-Shift\-q
Quit owm.
.SS Mouse commands
.TP
.B Mod\-Button1
Move focused window while dragging. Tiled windows will be toggled to the floating state.
.TP
.B Mod\-Button2
Toggles focused window between floating and tiled state.
.TP
.B Mod\-Button3
Resize focused window while dragging. Tiled windows will be toggled to the floating state.
.SH CUSTOMIZATION
owm is customized by directly changing the source code and (re)compiling the source
code. This keeps it fast, secure and simple.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR dmenu (1),
.BR st (1)
.SH ISSUES
Java applications which use the XToolkit/XAWT backend may draw grey windows
only. The XToolkit/XAWT backend breaks ICCCM-compliance in recent JDK 1.5 and early
JDK 1.6 versions, because it assumes a reparenting window manager. Possible workarounds
are using JDK 1.4 (which doesn't contain the XToolkit/XAWT backend) or setting the
environment variable
.BR AWT_TOOLKIT=MToolkit
(to use the older Motif backend instead) or running
.B xprop -root -f _NET_WM_NAME 32a -set _NET_WM_NAME LG3D
or
.B wmname LG3D
(to pretend that a non-reparenting window manager is running that the
XToolkit/XAWT backend can recognize) or when using OpenJDK setting the environment variable
.BR _JAVA_AWT_WM_NONREPARENTING=1 .
.SH BUGS
report all bug to https://github.com/parixitsapkota/owm/issues.
